  "prompt": "How can I prove that [math]\\sqrt{3} + 2[/math] is irrational?",
  "response": "To prove that \\(\\sqrt{3} + 2\\) is irrational, we will use a proof by contradiction. We'll assume that \\(\\sqrt{3} + 2\\) is rational and show that this leads to a contradiction.\n\n### Step-by-Step Proof:\n\n1. **Assume \\(\\sqrt{3} + 2\\) is rational.**\n\n   This means there exist integers \\(a\\) and \\(b\\) (with \\(b \\neq 0\\)) such that:\n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{3} + 2 = \\frac{a}{b}\n   \\]\n\n2. **Isolate \\(\\sqrt{3}\\).**\n\n   From the assumption, we can rearrange the equation:\n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{3} = \\frac{a}{b} - 2\n   \\]\n\n3. **Simplify the right-hand side.**\n\n   We have:\n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{3} = \\frac{a - 2b}{b}\n   \\]\n\n   Since \\(a\\) and \\(b\\) are integers, \\(a - 2b\\) is also an integer. Thus, \\(\\frac{a - 2b}{b}\\) is a rational number.\n\n4. **Contradict the irrationality of \\(\\sqrt{3}\\).**\n\n   From the equation \\(\\sqrt{3} = \\frac{a - 2b}{b}\\), we are saying that \\(\\sqrt{3}\\) is rational because it is expressed as a ratio of integers. However, \\(\\sqrt{3}\\) is known to be irrational, which contradicts our assumption that it can be expressed as a rational number.\n\n### Conclusion:\n\nSince assuming that \\(\\sqrt{3} + 2\\) is rational leads to a contradiction, our original assumption must be false. Therefore, \\(\\sqrt{3} + 2\\) is irrational.",
